so this chapter is pretty much easy as long as you remember how bytes and bits work in asm

a 32 bit register can be sliced in order to achive the perfect result 

for example, imagine theres a 32 bit register EBX 
we have to put the value of 2 into EBX
we make this 2 via a DB (define byte(8 bits))
so

number db 2 

so ebx is 32 bit, if we just put db into ebx, it wont work, it will be a garbage number 

instead we have to be memory efficent. 

EBX(32 bits) can be split into BX (16 bits)
BX can be split into BL and BH, which are both 8 bits. 
    Where BL -> byte LOW, BH -> byte HIGH

Whats the difference?

BL is basically is like the start of any binary, we start from power of 0 to 8 
so for example it starts at 0 * 2^0 and it increments based of how many bits

but in BH its different. BH starts at the 2^8.
so for example in our problem 
num db 2 
mov BH, [num]
it would result in 256 (2 * 2^8)
